This article is a component of a larger series detailing the [Politics of Scotland](/Category:Politics_of_Scotland), which itself falls under the umbrella of the [Politics of the United Kingdom](/Category:Politics_of_the_United_Kingdom). It focuses specifically on the diverse array of political entities that operate within Scotland.

### The Crown

The [Crown](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom) is the constitutional embodiment of the sovereign power in the United Kingdom.

*   **[The Monarch](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom):** Currently, [Charles III](/Charles_III) holds the position of Monarch. His reign signifies the continuation of a long-standing tradition of monarchy in the British Isles.
*   **[Heir apparent](/Succession_to_the_British_throne):** The direct line of succession places [William](/William,_Prince_of_Wales), who also holds the Scottish title of [Duke of Rothesay](/Duke_of_Rothesay), as the heir apparent.
*   **[Prerogative](/Royal_prerogative_in_the_United_Kingdom):** This refers to the residual powers and privileges vested in the Crown, exercised by the Monarch or their representatives.
*   **[Royal family](/British_royal_family):** The extended family of the Monarch, whose members play various ceremonial and public roles.
*   **[Succession](/Succession_to_the_British_throne):** The established order by which the Crown passes from one monarch to the next, governed by specific laws and traditions.
*   **[Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom):** An ancient British governmental institution, advising the Monarch in their duties. It plays a significant role in the UK's constitutional framework.
*   **[Union of the Crowns](/Union_of_the_Crowns):** Historically, this refers to the event in 1603 when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne, uniting the crowns of Scotland and England under a single monarch, though the parliaments remained separate.
*   **[Balmoral Castle](/Balmoral_Castle):** A private residence of the Monarch in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, often used as a summer retreat.
*   **[Holyrood Palace](/Holyrood_Palace):** The official residence of the Monarch in Scotland, located in Edinburgh. It serves as the venue for state ceremonies and official entertaining.
*   **[Scottish republicanism](/Scottish_republicanism):** A political movement advocating for the abolition of the monarchy in Scotland and the establishment of a republic.

### Executive

The executive branch of the Scottish Government is responsible for the day-to-day administration of Scotland.

*   **[Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government):** The devolved government for Scotland, responsible for a wide range of policy areas.
    *   **[Swinney government](/Swinney_government):** The current administration, led by the First Minister.
*   **[First Minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland):** The head of the Scottish Government. Currently, [The Rt Hon](/The_Rt_Hon) [John Swinney](/John_Swinney) [MSP](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament) holds this office.
*   **[Keeper of the Great Seal](/Keeper_of_the_Great_Seal_of_Scotland):** A senior ministerial role, currently held by [The Rt Hon](/The_Rt_Hon) [John Swinney](/John_Swinney) [MSP](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament), responsible for the Great Seal of Scotland.
*   **[Deputy First Minister](/Deputy_First_Minister_of_Scotland):** The second-highest position in the Scottish Government, currently held by [Kate Forbes](/Kate_Forbes) [MSP](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament).
*   **[Cabinet Secretaries](/Scottish_Government):** Ministers responsible for specific government departments.
*   **[Junior Ministers](/Scottish_Government):** Ministers who support Cabinet Secretaries.
*   **[Scottish budget](/Scottish_budget):** The financial plan for Scotland, outlining government spending and revenue.
*   **[Taxation](/Taxation_in_Scotland):** The system of levying taxes within Scotland, with devolved powers over certain tax areas.
*   **[Directorates](/Directorates_of_the_Scottish_Government):** The administrative divisions within the Scottish Government.
*   **[Executive agencies](/Executive_agencies_of_the_Scottish_Government):** Bodies that operate at arm's length from the Scottish Government, delivering specific public services.
*   **[Public bodies](/Public_bodies_of_the_Scottish_Government):** Organizations established by the Scottish Parliament or Government to carry out specific functions.
*   **[State-owned enterprises](/State-owned_enterprises_of_the_United_Kingdom):** Companies in which the state holds a significant stake, though this is less common in devolved areas.
*   **[Bute House:** The official residence of the First Minister of Scotland in Edinburgh.
*   **[St Andrew's House:** A prominent building in Edinburgh housing various government departments.
*   **[International relations](/International_relations_of_Scotland):** Scotland's engagement with other countries and international organizations, within the framework of UK foreign policy.

### Legislature

The legislative power in Scotland rests with the Scottish Parliament.

*   **[Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament):** The devolved unicameral legislature for Scotland, located in Edinburgh.
    *   **[Sixth session](/6th_Scottish_Parliament):** The current parliamentary term.
*   **[Presiding Officer](/Presiding_Officer_of_the_Scottish_Parliament):** The speaker of the Scottish Parliament, currently [Alison Johnstone](/Alison_Johnstone) [MSP](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament).
*   **[Primary legislation](/Act_of_the_Scottish_Parliament):** Laws passed by the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[Statutory instrument](/Scottish_statutory_instrument):** Secondary legislation made under powers granted by Acts of the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[Committees](/Committees_of_the_Scottish_Parliament):** Groups of MSPs that scrutinize legislation and government policy.
*   **[First Minister's Questions](/First_Minister%27s_Questions_(Scottish_Parliament)):** A regular session where the First Minister answers questions from MSPs.
*   **[Standards Commission for Scotland](/Standards_Commission_for_Scotland):** An independent body overseeing ethical standards for MSPs and public appointments.
*   **[Scotland Act 1998](/Scotland_Act_1998):** The foundational legislation that established the Scottish Parliament and devolved powers.
*   **[2012 Act](/Scotland_Act_2012):** A subsequent Act that further devolved powers to the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[2016 Act](/Scotland_Act_2016):** Another piece of legislation that enhanced the powers of the Scottish Parliament, particularly in relation to taxation.
*   **[Scottish Adjacent Waters Boundaries Order 1999](/Scottish_Adjacent_Waters_Boundaries_Order_1999):** Defines the maritime boundaries of Scotland.
*   **[EU Continuity Act 2020](/UK_Withdrawal_from_the_European_Union_(Continuity)_(Scotland)_Act_2020):** Legislation to ensure continuity of law after the UK's withdrawal from the [European Union](/European_Union).

### Law and justice

The legal system in Scotland is distinct from the rest of the UK.

*   **[Cabinet Secretary for Justice](/Cabinet_Secretary_for_Justice_and_Home_Affairs):** The minister responsible for justice matters, currently [Angela Constance](/Angela_Constance) [MSP](/Member_of_the_Scottish_Parliament).
*   **[Lord Advocate](/Lord_Advocate):** The chief legal officer of the Crown in Scotland, currently [Dorothy Bain](/Dorothy_Bain) [KC](/King%27s_Counsel).
*   **[Lord President](/Lord_President_of_the_Court_of_Session):** The head of the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session) and the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary), Scotland's supreme civil and criminal courts respectively. Currently, [The Rt Hon](/The_Rt_Hon) [Lord Pentland](/Paul_Cullen,_Lord_Pentland) [KC](/King%27s_Counsel) [PC](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom) holds this position.
*   **[Scots law](/Scots_law):** The unique legal system of Scotland, a hybrid of civil and common law traditions.
*   **[Udal law](/Udal_law):** A form of customary law historically found in Orkney and Shetland, with Norse origins.
*   **[Courts](/Courts_of_Scotland):** The judicial system of Scotland, comprising various levels of courts.
*   **[Judiciary](/Judiciary_of_Scotland):** The body of judges in Scotland.
*   **[Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service](/Scottish_Courts_and_Tribunals_Service):** An agency responsible for the administration of courts and tribunals in Scotland.
*   **[Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service](/Crown_Office_and_Procurator_Fiscal_Service):** Scotland's national prosecution service.
*   **[Police Scotland]:** The national police force for Scotland.
*   **[Scottish Prison Service]:** The agency responsible for managing prisons in Scotland.
*   **[Advocate General](/Advocate_General_for_Scotland):** The chief legal advisor to the UK Government on devolved matters in Scotland.
*   **[Solicitor General](/Solicitor_General_for_Scotland):** The second-ranking legal officer in Scotland.

### Elections and referendums

Scotland participates in various elections at different levels.

*   **[Scottish Parliament elections](/Elections_in_Scotland):** Held every five years to elect Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs).
    *   [1999](/1999_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   [2003](/2003_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   [2007](/2007_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   [2011](/2011_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   [2016](/2016_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   [2021](/2021_Scottish_Parliament_election)
    *   Next
*   **[United Kingdom Parliament elections](/Elections_in_Scotland):** Elections for Members of Parliament (MPs) representing Scottish constituencies in the UK House of Commons. This section lists historical general elections in Scotland, starting from [1801](/1801_co-option) up to [2019](/2019_United_Kingdom_general_election_in_Scotland).
*   **[European Parliament elections](/Elections_in_Scotland):** These were held in Scotland as part of the UK's membership of the [European Union](/European_Union), from [1979](/1979_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom) to [2019](/2019_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom).
*   **[Local elections](/Elections_in_Scotland):** Elections for councillors in Scotland's local government areas, with historical elections listed from [1967](/1967_Scottish_local_elections) to [2022](/2022_Scottish_local_elections).
*   **[Referendums](/Elections_in_Scotland):** Significant referendums have taken place in Scotland, including on [European Communities membership](/1975_United_Kingdom_European_Communities_membership_referendum) in 1975, [devolution](/1979_Scottish_devolution_referendum) in 1979 and [1997](/1997_Scottish_devolution_referendum), the [Alternative Vote](/2011_United_Kingdom_Alternative_Vote_referendum) in 2011, [Scottish independence](/2014_Scottish_independence_referendum) in 2014, and [European Union membership](/2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) in 2016.
*   **[Scottish Parliament constituencies](/Scottish_Parliament_constituencies_and_electoral_regions_from_2011):** The electoral districts for the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[Scottish Parliament electoral regions](/Scottish_Parliament_constituencies_and_electoral_regions_from_2011):** Larger regions used for the proportional representation element of Scottish Parliament elections.
*   **[Scottish Westminster constituencies](/Scottish_Westminster_constituencies):** The electoral districts for UK Parliament elections in Scotland.
*   **[Proposed second independence referendum](/Proposed_second_Scottish_independence_referendum):** Discussions and proposals surrounding a potential second referendum on Scottish independence.
*   **[Electoral system](/Electoral_system_of_Scotland):** The methods used to conduct elections in Scotland.
*   **Political parties:** The various organizations that contest elections in Scotland.

### Scotland and the United Kingdom

This section outlines the relationship between Scotland and the wider United Kingdom government.

*   **[United Kingdom Government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom):** The central government of the United Kingdom.
    *   **[Starmer ministry](/Starmer_ministry):** The current UK government.
*   **[Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom):** The head of the UK Government, currently [The Rt Hon](/The_Rt_Hon) [Keir Starmer](/Keir_Starmer) [MP](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)).
*   **[Secretary of State for Scotland](/Secretary_of_State_for_Scotland):** The UK Government minister responsible for Scottish affairs, currently [The Rt Hon](/The_Rt_Hon) [Ian Murray](/Ian_Murray_(Scottish_politician)) [MP](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)).
*   **[Scottish devolution](/History_of_Scottish_devolution):** The process by which powers have been transferred from the UK Parliament to the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union):** The 1707 agreement that united the Kingdom of Scotland with the Kingdom of England to form the Kingdom of Great Britain.
*   **[House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom):** The lower house of the UK Parliament.
*   **[House of Lords](/House_of_Lords):** The upper house of the UK Parliament.
*   **[Scotland Office](/Office_of_the_Secretary_of_State_for_Scotland):** The UK Government department responsible for Scotland.
*   **[Scottish Affairs Committee](/Scottish_Affairs_Committee):** A select committee of the UK House of Commons that scrutinizes the work of the Scotland Office and its impact on Scotland.
*   **[Scottish Grand Committee](/Scottish_Grand_Committee):** A former committee of the UK House of Commons composed of MPs representing Scottish constituencies.
*   **[Interministerial Standing Committee](/Interministerial_Standing_Committee):** A forum for cooperation between UK government ministers and devolved administration ministers.
*   **[Barnett formula](/Barnett_formula):** The mechanism used to adjust public spending in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland in response to changes in spending in England.
*   **[Reserved matters](/Reserved_and_excepted_matters):** Areas of policy that remain under the control of the UK Parliament, not devolved to the Scottish Parliament.
*   **[Sewel motion](/Legislative_consent_motion):** A mechanism whereby the Scottish Parliament grants consent for the UK Parliament to legislate on devolved matters.

