### Political Parties in Scotland

This article lists the various political parties that operate within Scotland.

#### Overview

*   **[Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party) (SNP):** The dominant force in Scottish politics, advocating for [Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence) and further [devolution](/Devolution_in_the_United_Kingdom). Generally [centre-left](/Centre-left) and [social democratic](/Social_democracy), it also champions [nuclear disarmament](/Nuclear_disarmament) and close ties with the [European Union](/European_Union). Founded in 1934, it established a permanent presence in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) in 1967. Its performance in the [general election of October 1974](/October_1974_United_Kingdom_general_election) saw it win 11 Westminster seats, though this was reduced significantly by [1979](/1979_United_Kingdom_general_election). Under [Alex Salmond](/Alex_Salmond), the SNP achieved a historic majority in the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) in the [2011 Scottish Parliament election](/2011_Scottish_Parliament_election), forming the Scottish Government. The current First Minister is [John Swinney](/John_Swinney). The party holds 64 Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs) and 9 Members of the UK Parliament (MPs).

*   **[Scottish Conservatives](/Scottish_Conservatives):** The Scottish arm of the UK [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)). Formed in 1965 from the merger of the [Scottish Unionist Party](/Unionist_Party_(Scotland)), which had been a major political force, winning a majority of Scottish seats in the [1931 general election](/1931_United_Kingdom_general_election) and [1955 general election](/1955_United_Kingdom_general_election). The party experienced a decline, losing all its Scottish seats in the [1997 general election](/1997_United_Kingdom_general_election). However, it secured 18 seats in the [1999 Scottish Parliament election](/1999_Scottish_Parliament_election) due to the [proportional representation](/Proportional_representation) electoral system. From 2001 to 2017, it held only one UK Parliament seat, but saw a resurgence in the [2017 general election](/2017_United_Kingdom_general_election), winning 13 seats. As a [centre-right](/Centre-right) party, it advocates [conservatism](/Conservatism_in_the_United_Kingdom) and [British unionism](/British_unionism). It currently has 31 MSPs, led by [Douglas Ross](/Douglas_Ross_(Scottish_politician)) until recently, and 5 MPs.

*   **[Scottish Labour](/Scottish_Labour):** The Scottish branch of the UK-wide [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)). It was the leading party in Scotland from 1964 to 2007. Adhering to [centre-left](/Centre-left) principles and promoting [British unionism](/British_unionism), it first surpassed the Conservatives in Scottish Westminster seats at the [1959 general election](/1959_United_Kingdom_general_election). In 1997, the UK Labour government under [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair) facilitated a [referendum on devolution](/1997_Scottish_devolution_referendum), which was overwhelmingly supported. Labour governed in coalition with the Liberal Democrats in the Scottish Parliament from 1999 to 2007. Following significant defeats, the party has seen leadership changes, including [Iain Gray](/Iain_Gray), [Johann Lamont](/Johann_Lamont), [Jim Murphy](/Jim_Murphy), [Kezia Dugdale](/Kezia_Dugdale), and [Richard Leonard](/Richard_Leonard). The current leader is [Anas Sarwar](/Anas_Sarwar) MSP. The party holds 37 MPs and 22 MSPs. [Note: A citation is needed for the claim about British unionism.]

*   **[Scottish Liberal Democrats](/Scottish_Liberal_Democrats):** The Scottish section of the UK [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)). This [centrist](/Centrism), [social liberal](/Social_liberal) and [British unionist](/British_unionist) party emerged from the merger of the [Liberal Party](/Liberal_Party_(UK)) and the [Social Democratic Party](/Social_Democratic_Party_(UK)) in 1988. The party's leader is [Alex Cole-Hamilton](/Alex_Cole-Hamilton). The [Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition](/Cameron%E2%80%93Clegg_coalition) at Westminster led to a significant decline in support. The party won five seats in the [2011 Scottish parliamentary election](/2011_Scottish_Parliament_election) and lost its Scottish MEP in the [2014 European elections](/2014_European_Parliament_election_in_the_United_Kingdom). At the [2015 general election](/2015_United_Kingdom_general_election), it retained only one MP, [Alistair Carmichael](/Alistair_Carmichael). The party currently has four MSPs and six MPs.

*   **[Scottish Greens](/Scottish_Greens):** Positioned between the [centre-left](/Centre-left_politics) and the [left-wing](/Left-wing_politics), the party champions [green politics](/Green_politics), [Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence), [equality](/Egalitarianism), and [radical democracy](/Radical_democracy). Originating from the breakup of the UK [Green Party](/Green_Party_(UK)), it now operates independently from the [Green Party of England and Wales](/Green_Party_of_England_and_Wales) and the [Green Party Northern Ireland](/Green_Party_Northern_Ireland). The Scottish Greens first gained a seat in the Scottish Parliament in 1999 and currently hold 7 MSPs, but have not yet returned any MPs to the UK Parliament.

*   **Reform UK Scotland:** The Scottish branch of the UK-wide [Reform UK](/Reform_UK). It is characterized by its [Eurosceptic](/Euroscepticism) and [right-wing populist](/Right-wing_populism) stance. The party gained its first elected representative in January 2021 when [Michelle Ballantyne](/Michelle_Ballantyne), a former Conservative MSP, joined the party. Ballantyne had previously resigned from the Conservatives. However, she lost her seat in the 2021 Scottish Parliament election, leaving Reform UK Scotland without elected representation at that time.

